custom%5C%22%20data-type%3D%5C%22embed%5C%22%3E%3Ciframe%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fdatawrapper.dwcdn.net%2F7UUlt%2F1%2F%5C%22%20title%3D%5C%22Income%20and%20hours%5C%22%20data-external%3D%5C%221%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22299%5C%22%3E%3C%2Fiframe%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%3Cp%3EOn%20average%2C%20employed%20young%20adults%20with%20at%20least%20one%20parent%20in%20the%20household%20weren't%20working%20as%20many%20hours%20or%20making%20as%20much%20money%20as%20their%20peers%20who%20didn't%20have%20a%20parent%20in%20the%20household.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAccording%20to%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.pewresearch.org%2Fshort-reads%2F2025%2F04%2F17%2Fthe-shares-of-young-adults-living-with-parents-vary-widely-across-the-us%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EPew%20Research%20Center%3C%2Fa%3E%20researcher%20Richard%20Fry%2C%20who%20authored%20a%20recent%20report%20on%20where%20in%20the%20country%C2%A0younger%20Americans%20live%20with%20their%20parents%2C%20young%20people%20are%20more%20likely%20to%20live%20with%20their%20parents%20when%20jobs%20are%20hard%20to%20come%20by%20and%20wages%20are%20stagnant.%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.pewresearch.org%2Fsocial-trends%2F2014%2F07%2F17%2Fin-post-recession-era-young-adults-drive-continuing-rise-in-multi-generational-living%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EPew%3C%2Fa%3E%20previously%20found%20the%20share%20of%20people%20living%20in%20multigenerational%20households%20surged%20during%20the%20Great%20Recession%20and%20continued%20rising%20afterward.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%20data-toc-id%3D%5C%2236966a4d-4d5a-4352-9136-79f7c6e47186%5C%22%3ELiving%20at%20home%20can%20also%20mean%20being%20disconnected%20from%20work%20and%20school%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EThere%20are%20those%20who%20choose%20to%20live%20at%20home%20for%20family%20connection%20and%20financial%20convenience%2C%20and%20there%20are%20others%20who%20don't%20have%20a%20choice.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ESo-called%20disconnected%20youth%20who%20aren't%20employed%20or%20in%20school%20made%20up%20about%2011%25%20of%20the%2016%20to%2024%20age%20group%20in%202022%2C%20per%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fmeasureofamerica.org%2Fyouth-disconnection-2024%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ea%202024%20report%3C%2Fa%3E%20from%20the%20research%20firm%20Measure%20of%20America.%20This%20cohort%20was%20more%20likely%20than%20their%20peers%20to%20live%20in%20poverty%2C%20lack%20health%20insurance%2C%20and%20receive%20government%20aid.%20Minorities%20and%20young%20people%20of%20color%20have%20higher%20rates%20of%20disconnection.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BThese%20are%20creative%20young%20people%20who%2C%20for%20a%20whole%20host%20of%20reasons%2C%20haven't%20had%20the%20opportunities%20or%20the%20support%20they've%20needed%20to%20explore%20what%20they%20want%20to%20do%20and%20figure%20out%20how%20to%20transition%20to%20adulthood%20in%20a%20way%20that's%20exciting%20for%20them%2C%26quot%3B%20said%20Megan%20Millenky%2C%20a%20senior%20research%20associate%20at%20MRDC%20who%20studies%20youth%20development.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIn%20an%20unsteady%20economy%2C%20it's%20unlikely%20that%20Gen%20Z%20and%20younger%20millennials'%20interest%20in%20living%20at%20home%20will%20fade%20anytime%20soon.%20And%2C%20as%20Millenky%20said%2C%20the%20group%20reflects%20%26quot%3Bquite%20a%20spectrum%26quot%3B%20of%20America's%20socioeconomic%20ladder.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cdiv%3ERead%20the%20original%20article%20on%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Femployed-college-young-adults-living-at-home-with-parents-2025-6%5C%22%3EBusiness%20Insider%3C%2Fa%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%22%2C%22published%22%3A1750404062000%2C%22visual%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F68518e5c3d5881a51c1b8fdf%3Fformat%3Djpeg%22%2C%22originID%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Femployed-college-young-adults-living-at-home-with-parents-2025-6%22%2C%22summary%22%3A%22Employed%2C%20in%20college%2C%20or%20somewhere%20in%20between%2C%20many%20young%20adults%20are%20still%20living%20with%20their%20parents